value.value: Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the neck of a fungal bud before and during cytokinesis.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of a growing fungal bud.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of a growing fungal hypha.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of the mating projection in unicellular fungi exposed to mating pheromone.

A positive regulation of gene expression mechanism that allows RNA polymerase to continue transcription beyond a termination site, thus allowing expression of downstream genes under specific conditions.
The cellular process in which the contractile ring cytokinetic ring attains its fully functional state.

label.value: mitotic cell size control checkpoint signaling

value.value: A signal transduction process that contributes to a cell size control checkpoint during mitosis.

label.value: mitotic G1 cell size control checkpoint signaling

value.value: A signal transduction process that contributes to a cell size control checkpoint during the G1/S transition of the cell cycle.

label.value: mitotic G2 cell size control checkpoint signaling

value.value: A signal transduction process that contributes to a cell size control checkpoint prior to the G2/M transition of mitosis.

A signaling process that controls cell cycle progression in response to changes in DNA structure by monitoring the integrity of the DNA. The DNA integrity checkpoint begins with detection of DNA damage, defects in DNA structure or DNA replication, and progresses through signal transduction and ends with cell cycle effector processes.

label.value: mitotic G1 DNA damage checkpoint signaling

value.value: A signal transduction process that contributes to a mitotic cell cycle G1/S transition DNA damage checkpoint.

label.value: mitotic intra-S DNA damage checkpoint signaling

value.value: A mitotic cell cycle checkpoint that slows DNA synthesis in response to DNA damage by the prevention of new origin firing and the stabilization of slow replication fork progression.
A signaling process that that controls a cell cycle checkpoint that originates from the mitotic or meiotic spindle.

definition.value: Note that this term should not be used for direct manual annotation as it should always be possible to choose either a mitotic or meiotic child term.

value.value: A signaling process that monitors and signals errors in the placement or orientation of the spindle in the cell. This delays the completion of anaphase until errors are corrected.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of membrane rafts, small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalize cellular processes.
The process that establishes the spatial arrangement of membrane rafts within a cellular membrane.

Assembly of hemidesmosomes, integrin-containing protein complexes that bind to laminin in the basal lamina. Hemidesmosomes form the contact between the basal surface of epithelial cells and the underlying basal lamina.

label.value: replication fork arrest at rDNA repeats

value.value: A process that impedes the progress of the DNA replication fork at natural replication fork pausing sites within the eukaryotic rDNA repeat spacer.

label.value: phospholipase D-activating G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway

value.value: A G protein-coupled receptor signaling pathway in which the signal is transmitted via the activation of phospholipase D (PLD) and a subsequent increase in the intracellular concentration of phosphatidic acid (PA).

definition.value: This term is intended to cover steps in a GPCR signaling pathway both upstream and downstream of phospholipase D (PLD) activation.

value.value: Any process that initiates the activity of inactive phospholipase D.

label.value: regulation of inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel activity

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of the inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel.

label.value: negative regulation of inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel activity

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of the inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel.

label.value: positive regulation of inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel activity

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of the inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate-sensitive calcium-release channel.
A protein complex that possesses nucleotide-dependent protein kinase activity. The nucleotide can be AMP (in S. pombe and human) or ADP (in S. cerevisiae).
The attachment of a cell to the underlying substrate via adhesion molecules.

The chemical reactions and pathways involving wybutosine, 3H-imidazo[1,2-alpha]purine-7-butanoic acid, 4,9-dihydro- alpha-[(methoxycarbonyl)amino]- 4,6-dimethyl-9-oxo- 3-beta-D-ribofuranosyl methyl ester, a modified nucleoside found in some tRNA molecules.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of wybutosine, 3H-imidazo[1,2-alpha]purine-7-butanoic acid, 4,9-dihydro- alpha-[(methoxycarbonyl)amino]- 4,6-dimethyl-9-oxo- 3-beta-D-ribofuranosyl methyl ester, a modified nucleoside found in some tRNA molecules.

definition.value: Note that wybutosine is a hypermodified G-residue, formerly called the Y-base, and its derivatives are exclusively found at position 37 (anticodon loop) of tRNAPhe.

value.value: An amorphous structure surrounding the core of the centrosome, from which microtubules are nucleated; contains gamma-tubulin.

definition.value: Note that the centrosomal corona has been observed in Dictyostelium, and is the functional equivalent of pericentriolar material.

value.value: Binding to a protein upon poly-ubiquitination of the target protein.

The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential.

definition.value: In vertebrates, the term 'neuromuscular junction' is limited to synapses targeting skeletal muscle fibers - all of which are cholinergic and excitatory. Both inhibitory and excitatory neuromuscular junctions exist in invertebrates, utilizing a range of neurotransmitters including glutamate, GABA and 5-HT.

value.value: A proteasome found in the nucleus of a cell.
A proteasome complex found in the cytosol of a cell.
The regulatory subcomplex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.

A multisubunit complex located in the cytosol of a cell, which caps one or both ends of the proteasome core complex. This complex recognizes, unfolds ubiquitinated proteins and translocates them to the proteasome core complex.
The core complex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.
The core complex of a proteasome located in the cytosol of a cell.

label.value: nuclear proteasome core complex, alpha-subunit complex

value.value: The subunits forming the outer ring of the core complex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.

label.value: cytosolic proteasome core complex, alpha-subunit complex

value.value: The proteasome core subcomplex that constitutes the two outer rings of the cytosolic proteasome core complex.

label.value: nuclear proteasome core complex, beta-subunit complex

value.value: The subunits forming the inner ring of the core complex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.

label.value: cytosolic proteasome core complex, beta-subunit complex

value.value: The proteasome core subcomplex that constitutes the two inner rings of the cytosolic proteasome core complex.

label.value: nuclear proteasome regulatory particle, base subcomplex

value.value: The subunits of the regulatory particle that directly associate with the core complex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.

label.value: cytosolic proteasome regulatory particle, base subcomplex

value.value: The subcomplex of the proteasome regulatory particle that directly associates with the proteasome core complex located in the cytosol of the cell.

label.value: nuclear proteasome regulatory particle, lid subcomplex

value.value: The subunits that form the peripheral lid of the regulatory particle of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.

label.value: cytosolic proteasome regulatory particle, lid subcomplex

value.value: The subcomplex of the cytosolic proteasome regulatory particle that forms the peripheral lid, which is added on top of the base subcomplex.
A centrosome from which one pole of a mitotic or meiotic spindle is organized.

label.value: homologous chromosome orientation in meiotic metaphase I

value.value: The cell cycle process in which the sister centromeres and kinetochores of one chromosome are fused and orientated so the chromosomes attach to microtubules that emanate from the same spindle pole. This process ensures that homologous l chromosomes are segregated at anaphase of meiosis I.
Any process that modulates the rate or extent of fever generation.
Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the rate or extent of fever generation.
Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of fever generation.

A receptor-mediated endocytosis process that results in the movement of receptors from the plasma membrane to the inside of the cell. The process begins when cell surface receptors are monoubiquitinated following ligand-induced activation. Receptors are subsequently taken up into endocytic vesicles from where they are either targeted to the lysosome or vacuole for degradation or recycled back to the plasma membrane.
